Бұл мақалада аграрлық секторға инновациялық технологияларды енгізудің
экономикалық тиімділігіне кешенді талдау ұсынылған. Зерттеу халықаралық
тәжірибені жүйелі талдау мен Қазақстан Республикасына бейімделген үлгі
әзірлеуге негізделген.

Зерттеу 2018-2024 жылдар аралығында инновациялық даму деңгейі әртүрлі
жеті елдің - АҚШ, Нидерланд, Израиль, Германия, Қытай, Үндістан және
Бразилияның ауыл шаруашылығы кәсіпорындарын қамтиды.

Салыстырмалы талдау нәтижесінде инновацияларды енгізу деңгейлерінде
елеулі айырмашылықтар анықталды: дамыған елдерде - 75-85\%, дамушы
экономикада - 30-50\%, ал Қазақстанда - 5\%-дан төмен. Инновациялық
белсенділік деңгейі мен экономикалық нәтижеліліктің негізгі
көрсеткіштері - еңбек өнімділігі, инвестициялардың рентабельдігі (ROI)
және экспорттық бәсекеге қабілеттілік арасында берік оң корреляция
орнатылды. Мысалы, Нидерландта ROI 300\%-ға жетсе, Қазақстанда ол небәрі
80\%-ды құрайды.

Зерттеу барысында инновацияларды табысты енгізудің негізгі
институционалдық, технологиялық және ұйымдастырушылық детерминанттары
анықталды. Оларға ғылым, бизнес және мемлекеттің тиімді интеграциясы;
инновациялық инфрақұрылымның болуы; білікті адами ресурстарға қол
жеткізу; қаржыландыру тетіктерінің болуы; сондай-ақ экспортқа
бағытталған стратегиялар жатады.

Қазақстанның аграрлық секторының диагностикалық талдауы институционалдық
және инфрақұрылымдық шектеулерді көрсетті, атап айтқанда: мемлекеттік
қолдаудың тиімсіз бөлінуі (тікелей субсидиялаудың басым болуы), ғылым
мен өндіріс арасындағы өзара іс-қимылдың әлсіздігі, сондай-ақ озық
агротехнологияларға қол жеткізудің шектеулілігі.

Аталған сын-қатерлерге жауап ретінде институционалдық, технологиялық,
қаржылық, білім беру және инфрақұрылымдық модульдерді қамтитын бес
компонентті инновациялық даму үлгісі ұсынылды. Үлгі кезең-кезеңімен іске
асыру тетіктерін және прогресті өлшейтін индикаторларды қарастырады,
сондай-ақ мемлекеттік-жекеменшік әріптестіктің маңыздылығын айқындайды.

Модельді 2033 жылға дейін іске асыру болжамдары инновациялық белсенді
кәсіпорындар үлесін 40\%-ға дейін арттыруға, еңбек өнімділігін
150-200\%-ға өсіруге, өндіріс шығындарын 20-30\%-ға қысқартуға және
аграрлық экспорт көлемін екі-үш есеге ұлғайтуға мүмкіндік бар екенін
көрсетеді.

Бұл зерттеу ауыл шаруашылығы экономикасы бойынша ғылыми әдебиетке үлес
қосып, қалыптасып келе жатқан экономикалардағы аграрлық салаларды
инновациялық бағытта дамытуға жүйелі көзқарасты ұсынады.

{\bfseries Түйін сөздер:} аграрлық инновациялар, экономикалық тиімділік,
технологияларды енгізу, еңбек өнімділігінің өсуі, Қазақстан ауыл
шаруашылығы, халықаралық тәжірибе, инновациялық даму үлгісі, ауыл
шаруашылығын жаңғырту, орнықты даму, агробизнестің трансформациясы.

{\bfseries Introduction.} The contemporary stage of agro-industrial complex
(AIC) development is marked by the growing role of innovative
technologies that drive productivity, sustainability, and
competitiveness in agriculture. In the context of global challenges
including climate change, population growth, and geopolitical
instability-the transition to innovation-based models of crop and
livestock production becomes a key factor in ensuring food security and
economic growth. This issue is especially relevant for the Republic of
Kazakhstan, where agriculture remains a strategically important sector
of the economy, providing rural employment, export potential, and
regional sustainability.

In recent years, Kazakhstan has shown an active commitment to
modernizing its AIC through the adoption of advanced technologies. In
crop production, this is reflected in the use of precision farming,
satellite monitoring, automated irrigation systems, and digital
platforms for enterprise management. In livestock production, key
innovation areas include genomic selection technologies, automated
feeding and health monitoring systems, and the development of smart
farms. Government support is provided through programs such as «Digital
Kazakhstan», «Agrobusiness-2025» and the «National Agro-Industrial
Development Project», which include subsidies for technological
upgrades, concessional lending, and the development of agricultural
science.

Nevertheless, despite ongoing efforts, the level of innovation adoption
within Kazakhstan's AIC remains uneven. Large agroholdings are actively
investing in modern technologies and demonstrating high economic
efficiency, while small and medium-sized farms face significant barriers
such as high implementation costs, a shortage of qualified personnel,
and insufficient infrastructural support. Moreover, a dependency on
imported technologies and equipment persists, limiting the sector's
sustainable development potential. In this context, a comprehensive
analysis of the economic effectiveness of innovative technologies in
Kazakhstan's crop and livestock sectors holds both academic and
practical importance.

Amid growing challenges related to food security and climate change, the
innovative development of the agro-industrial sector becomes a strategic
priority for national policy and research agendas. This is especially
critical for Kazakhstan, where agriculture plays a pivotal role in
domestic market provision and export development but struggles with low
productivity, limited access to modern technologies, and stark regional
disparities.

Numerous national and international scholars have addressed various
aspects of innovation in agriculture. Contributions to the methodology
for analyzing AIC economic development are found in the works of
Daribayeva A.K., Shulenbayeva F., and Bauer M. {[}1{]}. Recent
scientific discourse, especially against the backdrop of global
technological advancement, increasingly underscores the urgency of
innovation-led transformation in agriculture. While modern agricultural
enterprises are becoming active agents in innovation, Clancy M.S.,
Moschini G., and Heisey P. note that the sector largely depends on
external sources of technology and knowledge due to its relatively low
internal innovative capacity {[}2{]}.

Similarly, Bjerke L. and Johansson S. emphasize that the geographic
isolation of agricultural enterprises from urban and scientific hubs
limits their access to innovation infrastructure and resources {[}3{]}.
Andrade D., Pasini F., and Scarano F.R. argue that in countries
prioritizing high-tech sectors (e.g., IT, biomedicine, aerospace),
agriculture often falls outside the scope of national innovation
policies {[}4{]}.

Contemporary research emphasises the importance of socio-technical
innovation packages for the transformation of agri-food systems. Barrett
C.B., Benton T., Fanzo J. and colleagues argue that successful
agricultural modernisation requires a comprehensive approach that
combines technological, institutional and social innovations {[}5{]}.
This approach is particularly relevant for developing economies, where,
as Swinnen J. and Kuijpers R. note, inclusive value chains can
significantly accelerate poverty reduction and increase agricultural
productivity {[}6{]}.

This observation is particularly relevant for Kazakhstan: despite
isolated cases of innovation in crop and livestock production, the
agricultural sector as a whole remains under-attractive for investors
(Talymova L.A., Zhukenov B.M., Akenov S.Sh., et al.) {[}7{]}. Baudron F.
and Liégeois F. warn that neglecting the innovation vector may lead to
deteriorating food security, increased environmental stress, and
declining international competitiveness {[}8{]}.

According to Campos H. and Żak A., the need for agricultural innovation
today is driven not only by the imperative to increase productivity but
also by shrinking land and labor resources, especially amid rapid
urbanization {[}9,10{]}. Innovations represent the only viable mechanism
for compensating these losses.

Significant attention in contemporary literature is devoted to
digitalization as the primary vector of agricultural innovation. It is
viewed as a strategic enabler of production transformation, management
efficiency, and market integration (Abraliyev O.A., Sugirova G.S.,
Velesco S.; Kaldiyarov D.A., Kalymbekova Zh.K., Zhumanazarov K.B.;
Shaynurov A.S., Smagulova Zh.B.) {[}11-13{]}. Digital solutions enhance
farmers'{} capacities in planning, accounting, and
resource management, as highlighted by Shogenov B.A. and Mirzoeva A.R.
{[}14{]}.

Moreover, the relevance of innovation is closely tied to sustainable
development. Several authors emphasize that long-term competitiveness in
agriculture is unattainable without environmentally responsible
innovations that promote the sustainable use of natural resources
(Ferreira Apal, de Oliveira L., Talamini E.; Ndaba B., Roopnarain A.,
Haripriya R., et al.) {[}15,16{]}.

The objective of this study is to assess the economic effectiveness of
innovation implementation in agricultural enterprises based on
international experience and to develop an adapted model for Kazakhstan.
To achieve this, the study addresses the following tasks:

-сonduct a comparative analysis of innovation implementation in the
agricultural sectors of seven leading countries (USA, Netherlands,
Israel, Germany, China, India, Brazil) for the period 2018-2024;

- identify key success factors determining the economic efficiency of
innovation adoption in agriculture;

- assess the current status and challenges of innovation diffusion in
Kazakhstan's agricultural enterprises;

- develop a model for innovation implementation in Kazakhstan's
agricultural sector based on international experience and national
specificities;

- propose a methodology for evaluating economic efficiency and
forecasting the potential outcomes of the proposed model.

The scientific novelty of the study lies in the development of a
comprehensive model for innovation deployment in Kazakhstan's
agricultural sector, based on a systematic analysis of international
experience and adaptation of best practices to local conditions. The
proposed model accounts for economic, social, environmental, and
institutional dimensions of innovation, ensuring its comprehensiveness
and practical applicability.

Thus, the innovative transformation of Kazakhstan's agro-industrial
complex is not merely desirable but strategically imperative. Global
experience confirms that only the systemic adoption of advanced
agritechnologies can ensure the sustainable growth and resilience of the
sector.

{\bfseries Methodology and Materials.} The methodological basis of this
study is a systematic approach, within which the process of introducing
innovative technologies in the agricultural sector is viewed as a
complex multi-level system comprising interrelated economic,
technological, institutional and social components. This approach
provides a comprehensive understanding of the phenomenon under study and
helps to identify sustainable patterns that influence the effectiveness
of innovations in agriculture.

The comparative analysis is based on a multi-criteria evaluation system
that includes the following key indicators: the level of innovation
adoption, expressed as a percentage of enterprises using innovative
technologies; return on investment (ROI), calculated using a modified
formula that incorporates sustainable development factors; labour
productivity index with a base value of 2018 taken as 100\%; investment
intensity, measured as a share of gross domestic product in agriculture.

The data collection and processing procedure was carried out in
accordance with a structured protocol comprising five consecutive
stages. The first stage involved the selection of primary data sources
from the official databases of international organisations - the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), the Food
and Agriculture Organisation of the United Nations (FAO) and the World
Intellectual Property Organisation (WIPO). The second stage involved
validating the data obtained by cross-checking it with information from
the national statistical services of the countries under study. The
third stage involved analysing time series based on annual data for the
period 2018-2024. The fourth stage involved the application of
statistical methods, in particular Pearson' s correlation
analysis, in which a correlation coefficient of r \textgreater{} 0.7 was
interpreted as an indicator of a strong relationship. In the final fifth
stage, forecast models were developed based on linear regression with a
95\% confidence interval.

According to the latest report by the Asian Development Bank, digital
transformation in Central Asian agriculture shows significant potential
for increasing productivity, with Kazakhstan identified as the country
with the greatest potential for technological breakthroughs in the
region {[}17{]}. This confirms the need to intensify investment in the
innovative development of the industry.

The study used both general scientific methods (analysis, synthesis,
comparison, generalisation) and specialised methods of economic
research, including statistical analysis, econometric modelling and
graphical data visualisation. The comprehensive application of these
methods ensured the scientific validity and reproducibility of the
results obtained.

{\bfseries Results and discussion.} An analysis of international experience
indicates that over the past 20 years, developing economies have become
the primary drivers of global agricultural market growth-a trend
expected to continue into the next decade. The increase in agricultural
product consumption is mainly driven by population growth and rising
incomes in low- and middle-income countries.

According to the OECD-FAO Agricultural Outlook 2024-2033, China's
influence on global food consumption is declining, with its share in
global consumption growth projected to decrease from 28\% in the
previous decade to 11\% in the next. In contrast, India and Southeast
Asian countries are expected to account for 31\% of global consumption
growth by 2033.

A key trend is that the increase in crop production will primarily
result from productivity gains on existing agricultural lands, rather
than expansion of cultivated areas. A significant portion of growth in
the livestock and fisheries sectors will also stem from increased
productivity. However, despite expected productivity gains-especially in
low- and middle-income countries-substantial productivity gaps will
persist, posing challenges to farm incomes and food security.

From an environmental sustainability perspective, the intensity of
greenhouse gas emissions in agriculture is expected to decline.
Nevertheless, direct emissions from the agricultural sector are
projected to rise by 5\% in absolute terms. Halving food loss by 2030
could potentially reduce global agricultural emissions by 4\%.

For the comparative analysis, seven countries were selected that
represent various regions of the world and demonstrate successful
practices in implementing innovative technologies in agriculture: The
United States, Netherlands, Israel, Germany, China, India, and Brazil.
These countries were chosen due to their leading positions in different
aspects of agricultural innovation and their diverse approaches to
innovation implementation.

An analysis of data from 2018 to 2024 reveals significant differences in
the levels of innovation adoption across the agricultural sectors of the
studied countries {[}18 - 20{]} ( Fig.1).

{\bfseries Fig.1 - Level of innovation technology adoption in the
agricultural sector (2018-2024)}

As can be seen from the data presented in Figure 1, the highest level of
innovation technology adoption in the agricultural sector in 2024 is
recorded in developed countries. The Netherlands leads the way with
85\%, followed by the United States (80\%) and Israel and Germany (75\%
each). These figures reflect a high degree of technological maturity and
a sustainable investment policy in the field of agricultural innovation.

In countries with dynamically developing economies, the level of
innovation implementation varies at an average level: China demonstrates
an indicator of 50\%, India - 40\%, and Brazil - 30\%. This indicates a
gradual but purposeful movement of these countries towards the
technological modernisation of agriculture.

Kazakhstan, in turn, lags significantly behind both developed and
rapidly developing countries: the level of implementation of innovative
solutions in the agricultural sector was only 5\% in 2024. This
indicator points to a significant lag, requiring systematic measures of
state support and stimulation of technological development in the
industry.

Despite varying levels of involvement, all countries surveyed show
positive dynamics in the period from 2018 to 2024. The most pronounced
growth rates are observed in China (an increase of 25 percentage points)
and India (+20\%), which indicates the implementation of active
government policies aimed at introducing innovative solutions into
agricultural production. At the same time, growth in Kazakhstan was only
2\%, which may be due to institutional, financial and human resource
barriers to technological modernisation of the agro-industrial complex.

The economic efficiency of introducing innovative technologies, measured
by the return on investment (ROI) indicator, also varies significantly
between countries {[}19,21{]} (Fig.2).

{\bfseries Fig.2 - Economic Efficiency of Innovations in the Agricultural
Sector (2018-2024)}

According to the data presented, the highest rates of return on
investment in innovation in the agricultural sector in 2024 were
recorded in the Netherlands (300\%), the United States and Germany
(280\% each), and Israel (270\%). These figures indicate the high
effectiveness of innovation policy and a developed technology transfer
system in these countries.

Countries with rapidly developing economies show moderate levels of
return: China - 180\%, India - 150\%. These indicators reflect the
positive effect of investments in technological modernisation and the
introduction of advanced solutions, accompanied by an increase in
agricultural productivity.

Relatively low profitability values are observed in Brazil (120\%) and
Kazakhstan (80\%). Despite the positive dynamics, these values indicate
insufficient effectiveness in realising the innovative potential in the
agricultural sector of these countries, which may be due to structural
constraints, weak institutional support and limited access to advanced
technologies.

During the period 2018-2024, all countries analysed demonstrated growth
in the return on investment in innovation, which indicates an increase
in the effectiveness of the technologies being implemented and an
improvement in the conditions for their application. The most
significant increase in indicators was recorded in India and China, at
+60 percentage points. This is due to the active development of
innovation infrastructure, growth in investment in scientific research,
and improvements in the quality of the solutions being implemented. In
Kazakhstan, the increase was 40 percentage points, which is undoubtedly
a positive shift. Nevertheless, in absolute terms, the return on
investment remains low, which requires further systematic efforts to
increase the return on innovation.

The importance of government policy in stimulating innovation is
confirmed by the experience of Kazakhstan, where the National Project
for the Development of the Agro-Industrial Complex for 2021-2025
provides for the allocation of significant resources for the
technological modernisation of the industry {[}22{]}. However, as the
analysis shows, the key challenge remains the effective use of the
allocated funds.

The level of investment in agricultural innovation, measured as a
percentage of agricultural GDP, also varies significantly between
countries {[}16,21{]} (Fig.3).

{\bfseries Fig.3- Investments in agricultural innovation (2018-2024)}

An analysis of the distribution of investment resources in agricultural
innovation by country in 2024 allows us to identify a group of global
leaders demonstrating the highest level of investment relative to gross
domestic product in agriculture. Thus, in the United States, the share
of investment in agricultural innovation amounted to 3.2\% of
agricultural GDP, in Germany - 3.1\%, in the Netherlands - 3.0\%, and in
Israel - 2.8\%. These data reflect the sustained focus of these
countries on innovation-oriented development of the agro-industrial
complex, as well as the existence of effective mechanisms for financing
scientific and technical developments in agriculture.

China shows a moderate level of investment - 2.2\%, which nevertheless
indicates a growing focus on the development of agricultural
technologies as one of the priorities of state agricultural policy.
India, Brazil and Kazakhstan are characterised by significantly lower
indicators: 1.5\%, 1.2\% and 0.5\%, respectively. The level is
particularly low in Kazakhstan, which indicates limited funding for
innovation in the agricultural sector and the existence of institutional
and resource barriers.

At the same time, all countries showed growth in investment in
agricultural innovation between 2018 and 2024. The most pronounced
positive dynamics were recorded in China and India, where growth
amounted to +0.7 percentage points. This confirms the existence of a
sustainable trend towards strengthening state support and developing
innovative infrastructure in the agricultural sector. In Kazakhstan, the
increase was only 0.2 percentage points, which can be regarded as
insufficient progress in the context of global trends and continuing
technological backwardness.

One of the key indicators of the effectiveness of innovative technology
implementation is the growth of labour productivity in the agricultural
sector {[}21,23{]} (Fig.4).

{\bfseries Fig.4 - Labour productivity growth in the agricultural sector
(2018-2024)}

The data shows that the highest growth in labour productivity for the
period 2018-2024 is observed in China (180\%), India (160\%), the
Netherlands (150\%) and Germany (145\%). The United States, Israel and
Brazil show average figures: 140\%, 135\% and 130\% respectively.
Kazakhstan shows the lowest labour productivity growth among the
countries studied - 110\%.

-The base year was taken as 2018 (value = 100\%).

-The labour productivity growth index for 2024 was calculated for each
country.

-Labour productivity was measured as the volume of agricultural
production per worker.

It is important to note that there is a direct correlation between the
level of innovation technology adoption and labour productivity growth
(Fig.5).

\fig{e2/image2}{}

{\bfseries Fig.5 -Level of Innovation Implementation in 2018-2024 (\%)}

As can be seen in Figure 5, countries with higher levels of innovation
adoption tend to demonstrate higher labour productivity growth. However,
there are exceptions: China and India show higher productivity growth
with average levels of innovation adoption, which may be due to the «low
base» effect and higher growth potential in these countries.

The choice of a grain-producing enterprise for testing the model is
determined by the priorities of the National Project for the Development
of the Agro-Industrial Complex, where grain production is identified as
one of the key areas for the introduction of innovative technologies
{[}20{]}.

Based on an analysis of international experience, the following key
factors can be identified that determine the successful implementation
of innovative technologies in the agricultural sector:

Integration of science, business and government. The most successful
examples of innovation implementation are observed in countries where
effective interaction between scientific organisations, agricultural
enterprises and government structures has been established. A striking
example is the Netherlands, where Wageningen University and Research
Centre closely cooperates with farmers and agribusinesses with the
support of the state {[}18{]}.

Developed infrastructure and innovation ecosystem. Countries that are
leaders in innovation implementation (the United States, Germany, the
Netherlands) are characterised by a developed innovation infrastructure,
including research centres, technology parks, incubators, demonstration
farms and technology transfer centres.

Targeted state support. The successful examples of China and Israel
demonstrate the importance of targeted state policies to support
innovation in the agricultural sector. The key factor here is not so
much the amount of support as its focus on the development of
infrastructure and technologies, rather than direct subsidies {[}20{]}.

The technological component includes the introduction of socio-technical
innovation packages, the concept of which is detailed in the study by
Klerkx L and co-authors {[}24{]}. This approach involves not simply
borrowing technologies, but adapting them to local conditions, taking
into account social and environmental factors.

Education and training. Countries with high levels of innovation pay
particular attention to training qualified personnel for the
agricultural sector. For example, Germany and the Netherlands have
developed a dual education system that combines theoretical training
with practical training in enterprises.

Access to financing. A developed system of financing innovative
projects, including government programmes, private investment, venture
capital and specialised funds, is an important factor for success. The
United States leads the way in the development of venture financing in
the agricultural sector {[}24{]}.

Focus on exports and international competitiveness. Countries focused on
agricultural exports (the Netherlands, the United States, Brazil)
demonstrate a higher level of innovation, as international competition
stimulates increased efficiency and product quality.

Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector has significant
potential for development thanks to its vast land resources (more than
272 million hectares of agricultural land) and favourable climatic
conditions for growing various crops. However, despite this potential,
the level of innovation in agriculture remains extremely low. According
to a study conducted in 2024, the share of innovative technologies in
Kazakhstan' s agricultural production does not exceed 5\%
{[}18{]}. This is significantly lower than in developed countries
(75-85\%) and even in middle-income countries such as China (50\%) and
India (40\%).

Investment in agricultural innovation in Kazakhstan accounts for only
0.5\% of agricultural GDP, which is 6-7 times lower than in developed
countries. At the same time, most of the state support for the
agricultural sector is directed towards direct subsidies rather than
infrastructure and technology development {[}25{]}.

Labour productivity growth in Kazakhstan' s agricultural
sector for the period 2018-2024 was 110\%, which is the lowest among

the countries studied. This indicates the low efficiency of the
technologies and production methods used.

The return on investment in innovation in Kazakhstan' s
agricultural sector is 80\%, which is significantly lower than in other
countries. This is due to the inefficient use of investments,
insufficient infrastructure development and low staff qualifications.

Based on an analysis of the current situation, the following main
problems and barriers to the introduction of innovative technologies in
Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector can be identified:

Inefficient use of state support. Most state support is directed towards
direct subsidies rather than infrastructure and technology development.
According to a study conducted in 2024, about 70\% of state support for
Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector goes to direct
subsidies {[}25{]}.

Kazakhstan lacks adequate infrastructure for the storage, processing and
transportation of agricultural products, which leads to significant
losses and reduced production efficiency.

Weak integration of science and business. The lack of effective
mechanisms for interaction between scientific organisations and
agricultural enterprises hinders technology transfer and innovation
implementation.

The proposed model for introducing innovative technologies in
Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector is based on an analysis
of international experience and the adaptation of best practices, taking
into account national characteristics. The model is an integrated
ecosystem that combines the key elements of successful innovation
implementation identified in the analysis of the experience of leading
countries.

The key principles of the model are:

-Systematic and comprehensive approach - interconnected development of
all elements of the innovation ecosystem

-Results-oriented approach - priority of economic efficiency and
sustainability

-Adaptability - taking into account regional characteristics and
different types of farms

-Phased implementation - consistent implementation with measurable
results

-Public-private partnership - joint efforts of the state and business

Structural components of the model.

-The institutional component of the model is based on the experience of
the Netherlands (integration of science, business and the state) and
Israel (targeted state support). Proposed measures include:

- creation of a National Centre for Agricultural Innovation based on the
model of Wageningen University (Netherlands);

- formation of regional innovation clusters with the participation of
universities, research centres and agribusiness;

- reorientation of state support from direct subsidies to infrastructure
and technology development;

- developing a long-term strategy for innovative development of the
agro-industrial complex with clear KPIs.

The technological component of the model is based on the experience of
Israel (water-saving technologies), the United States (digitalisation
and automation) and Germany (precision farming). The proposed measures
include:

- introduction of a precision farming system adapted to the conditions
of Kazakhstan;

- development of water-saving technologies (drip irrigation, soil
moisture monitoring);

- creation of a digital platform for the agricultural sector with the
integration of IoT, big data and AI;

- development of automation and robotics in large farms;

- introduction of smart livestock farming technologies.

The financial component of the model is based on the experience of the
United States (venture capital financing) and China (government
investment in innovation). The proposed measures include:

- creation of a specialised agricultural innovation fund with public and
private capital;

- development of a preferential lending system for the introduction of
innovative technologies;

- introduction of mechanisms for insuring innovative risks;

- tax incentives for investments in agricultural innovation;

- development of leasing for innovative equipment and machinery.

The financial component is based on international experience in creating
inclusive financial mechanisms. As demonstrated by Swinnen J. and
Kuijpers R., access to finance is a critical factor for involving small
and medium-sized farms in innovation processes {[}23{]}.

The educational component of the model is based on the experience of the
Netherlands (integration of education and practice) and Germany (dual
education). The proposed measures include:

- modernisation of agricultural education with a focus on innovative
technologies;

- creation of demonstration farms at agricultural universities;

- development of exchange programmes with leading agricultural
universities around the worl;

- introduction of a system of continuing education for farmers and
agribusiness specialists;

- creation of an online platform for training in modern agricultural
technologies.

The infrastructure component of the model is based on the experience of
the Netherlands (logistics infrastructure) and Brazil (export
infrastructure). The proposed measures include:

- development of digital infrastructure in rural areas (broadband
Internet, mobile communications);

- creation of modern logistics centres for storage and processing of
products;

- modernisation of irrigation systems with the introduction of smart
technologies;

- development of transport infrastructure for product exports;

- creation of a network of innovation centres for demonstrating and
testing new technologies.

Based on an analysis of international experience and the current state
of Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector, the following
results of the proposed model' s implementation can be
predicted by 2033:

- increase in the share of enterprises implementing innovations from 5\%
to 40\%;

- growth in labour productivity in the agricultural sector by 150-200\%;

- reduction in production costs by 20-30\%;

- increase in agricultural exports by 2-3 times;

- reduction in water consumption per unit of production by 30-40\%;

- reduction of losses during storage and transportation by 50\%;

- creation of 50-70 thousand new jobs in the high-tech agricultural
sector.

The projected indicators are consistent with regional trends identified
by the Asian Development Bank, according to which Central Asian
countries could increase agricultural productivity by 40-60\% by 2030,
provided that they successfully undergo digital transformation {[}15{]}.

The forecast for productivity growth with an increase in the level of
innovation implementation in Kazakhstan is presented in Fig.6.

\fig{e2/image3}{}

{\bfseries Fig.e 6 - Level of innovation implementation \%}

As can be seen from Fig.6, increasing the level of innovation adoption
from the current 5\% to 40\% could lead to a 180\% increase in labour
productivity by 2033. This would significantly improve the
competitiveness of Kazakhstani agricultural products on international
markets and ensure the sustainable development of the agricultural
sector.

\begin{quote}
To assess the economic efficiency of introducing innovative technologies
in Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector, we propose using
the following formula (1). The proposed formula for assessing return on
investment is a modified approach to the traditional ROI calculation,
adapted to the specifics of Kazakhstan' s agricultural
sector:
\end{quote}

\(ROI = \frac{\Delta R - \Delta C}{I}*(1 + S*E)\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \)(1)

\begin{quote}
where:

ΔR - revenue increment determined by the functional dependence on the
technological and infrastructural components of the model;

ΔC - change in operating costs determined by the synergistic effect of
the financial and educational components;

I - total investment accumulated across all five components of the
model;

S is the sensitivity coefficient, set at 0.3 for Kazakhstan based on an
analysis of the volatility of the agricultural sector for the period
2018-2024;

E is the external effect coefficient, estimated at 0.2 and reflecting
the potential for export orientation.

The mechanism of interaction between the model components and the ROI
formula parameters is characterised by the following functional
dependencies:

The institutional component has a modulating effect on the sensitivity
coefficient S by ensuring the stability of agricultural policy, which
can change its value in the range of ±0.1. The technological component
demonstrates a direct positive correlation with revenue growth ΔR,
providing potential growth in the range of 20-30\% with full-scale
implementation. The financial component determines not only the volume
of investment I, but also the weighted average cost of capital,
affecting the discounting of future cash flows. The educational
component contributes to a 15-20\% reduction in operating costs ΔC by
improving staff qualifications and optimising production processes. The
infrastructure component increases the external effect coefficient E in
the range of 0.1-0.3 by improving access to domestic and international
markets.

To demonstrate the practical applicability of the developed model, we
will calculate the economic efficiency of introducing innovative
technologies using the example of a typical grain-producing farm in the
Akmola region with a land bank of 5,000 hectares, specialising in wheat
production.

The initial parameters of the farm at the beginning of 2024 are
characterised by the following indicators: annual revenue from sales is
500 million tenge with production costs of 350 million tenge, which
provides an operating profit of 150 million tenge. The planned
investment in innovative technologies, including precision farming
systems, satellite crop monitoring and automated equipment control, is
100 million tenge.

The projected results of the introduction of innovative technologies by
2026, based on an analysis of international experience and adapted to
the conditions of northern Kazakhstan, suggest the following dynamics:
revenue growth (ΔR) will amount to 125 million tenge, which is
equivalent to a 25\% increase from the baseline due to higher yields and
product quality; reduction in production costs (ΔC) will reach 70
million tenge, or 20\% of the baseline, thanks to optimised resource
use; the sensitivity coefficient (S) is assumed to be 0.3, reflecting
moderate volatility in the grain market; the external effect coefficient
(E) is estimated at 0.2, taking into account the potential for entering
export markets.

Applying formula (1) to calculate the return on investment gives the
following result:

\[ROI = \frac{125 - ( - 70)}{100}*(1 + 0,3*0,2) = \frac{195}{100}*1,06 = 2,067\]

The ROI value of 206.7\% indicates the high economic efficiency of
introducing innovative technologies with a payback period of less than
two years, confirming the feasibility of the proposed model for
Kazakhstan.

The architecture of the proposed model for introducing innovative
technologies in Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector is a
hierarchically organized system of interconnected components (Fig 7),
where each element performs a specific function in the overall mechanism
of industry transformation.

\fig{e2/image4}{}

{\bfseries Fig.7 - Integrated model for introducing innovations in
Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector}

The structure presented demonstrates the cascading nature of component
interaction, where the institutional component forms the regulatory and
legal framework through the creation of a National Innovation Centre,
the development of regional clusters, and the introduction of a system
of key performance indicators. The technological component ensures the
direct modernisation of production processes through the introduction of
precision farming, smart irrigation systems and a unified digital
management platform. The financial component creates the necessary
economic conditions through the formation of a specialised innovation
fund, preferential lending mechanisms and an innovation risk insurance
system. The educational component guarantees staffing through the
modernisation of university programmes, the creation of demonstration
farms and the development of online learning platforms. The
infrastructure component forms the material and technical base through
the development of digital networks, the construction of modern
logistics centres and the creation of export infrastructure.
\end{quote}

The financial component of the model is based on international
experience in creating inclusive financial mechanisms. As demonstrated
by Swinnen J. and Kuijpers R., access to finance is a critical factor
for involving small and medium-sized farms in innovation processes
{[}6{]}.

{\bfseries Conclusion.} The study demonstrated that the introduction of
innovative technologies in the agricultural sector is a key factor in
increasing its economic efficiency and competitiveness. International
experience shows that there is a direct correlation between the level of
innovation activity and growth in labour productivity, return on
investment and the sustainability of agricultural production.

The study showed that the introduction of innovative technologies in the
agricultural sector is a key factor in increasing its economic
efficiency and competitiveness. International experience demonstrates a
direct correlation between the level of innovation adoption and growth
in labour productivity, return on investment, and sustainability of
agricultural production.

An analysis of the experience of seven leading countries (the United
States, the Netherlands, Israel, Germany, China, India, and Brazil) has
identified key factors for the successful introduction of innovations,
including the integration of science, business and government,
infrastructure development, targeted government support, training,
access to finance and export orientation.

The current state of Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector is
characterised by a low level of innovation technology adoption (5\% of
enterprises), insufficient investment in innovation (0.5\% of
agricultural GDP) and low labour productivity growth (110\% for
2018-2024). The main problems are the inefficient use of state support,
insufficient infrastructure development, weak integration of science and
business, a shortage of skilled personnel, and limited access to
financing.

The proposed model for introducing innovative technologies in
Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector is based on an analysis
of international experience and the adaptation of best practices, taking
into account national characteristics. The model includes institutional,
technological, financial, educational and infrastructure components with
a phased implementation mechanism.

The projected results of the model' s implementation by
2033 include an increase in the share of enterprises implementing
innovations to 40\%, a 150-200\% increase in labour productivity, a
20-30\% reduction in production costs, and a 2-3-fold increase in
agricultural exports.

To assess the economic efficiency of innovation implementation, a
formula has been proposed that takes into account not only financial
indicators but also the contribution to environmental sustainability and
export potential.

The implementation of the proposed model will significantly increase the
economic efficiency of Kazakhstan' s agricultural sector,
ensure its sustainable development and competitiveness in international
markets.

The key to success is a systematic approach and consistent
implementation of all components of the model, taking into account
regional characteristics and different types of farms.

The proposed model is fully consistent with the strategic priorities of
the Republic of Kazakhstan, as set out in the Concept for the
Development of the Agro-Industrial Complex of the Republic of Kazakhstan
for 2021-2030 and the National Project for the Development of the
Agro-Industrial Complex for 2021-2025. The five-component structure of
the model corresponds to the five priority areas of the National
Project: institutional development, technological modernisation,
ensuring financial accessibility, human capital development and
infrastructure improvement. The implementation of the model will
contribute to the achievement of the target indicators of state
programmes, including a 2.5-fold increase in labour productivity by
2030, an increase in the share of processed agricultural products to
70\% and a twofold increase in exports of agro-industrial products.

